The article highlights the issue of stalking and its impact on the safety and well-being of men and women. It emphasizes that stalking is often underreported and unaddressed, which leaves victims feeling helpless and anxious. Stalkers use repeated and unwanted contact, threats, following, and harassment through social media to instill fear in their victims. The article mentions that young women are disproportionately victimized, but anyone can be affected. Most victims are stalked by someone they know, with those recently separated or divorced being at the highest risk. The government is working with state and local partners to prosecute stalkers and promote prevention strategies. The article concludes by expressing support for survivors, law enforcement professionals, and all who fight against stalking, and emphasizes the importance of letting victims know they are not alone and that help is available.